Part I - Exploring Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Gurinder Arora¶

Introduction¶

This dataset is provided by Udacity for a manual download. For GoBike is a regional public bike sharing system in San Francisko Bay Area. The dataset covers over 180K records of individual rides made in February 2019.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • The dataset has data about more than 180K individual bike rides from February 2019.
  • df.info() above shows the different columns and their dtypes

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • I would be interested in exploring the factors affecting the number and duration of bike trips.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • The columns that would be the usefull had been filtered above as the the dataframe df1 with the corrected dtypes. The information regarding that is available above as df1.info().

  • Exploring start hour
In [20]:
def count_plot(df1, xVar, color = 'steelblue', order = None):
    plt.figure(figsize = [14, 6])
    sns.countplot(data = df1, x = xVar, edgecolor = 'black', color = color, order = order)
    xVar = xVar.replace('_', ' ')
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {xVar}'''.title(), fontsize = 14, weight = 'bold')
    plt.xlabel(xVar.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency'.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
In [21]:
count_plot(df1, 'start_hour', color = sns.color_palette('tab10')[1])

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip duration had an unusual distribution, which for the exploration purposes was needed to be converted to minutes instead of seconds.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Yes there were unusual distributions, such as the age of riders. Age more than 100 is highly unlikely, and the age above 80 could be interpreted as outliers as well, which were cleaned for the exploration purposes. Other than that it was necessary to get some dtypes right.

Conclusions¶

Data Wrangling Process

  1. Missing values were removed.
  2. Outliers were removed.
  3. The columns not necessary for the exploration were removed.
  4. Dtypes were corrected in favor of the exploration process.

Data Visualization

  1. In the univariate exploration, single variables were taken into account to get an overview of further investigation.
  2. In the bivariate exploration, two variables were mixed to find interesting facts about the data (which have already been documented above). Furthermore new column was added to find more important information (start and end station combos).
  3. In the mutlivariate exploration, mutliples variables were mixed to find out further important information for the decision making purposes, from which one thing is very clear: The marketing efforts should more be focused on female centric bike riding specifications to have a significant increase in business.
